          Dysfunctional tactics from Emery and David Luiz showed why it's dangerous to put him in a back 4. Not sure why he doesn't have an error next to his name for Salah's 2nd. Luiz should gave watched how Rob Holding had Mo in his pocket last season at the Emirates, you don't dive in at a player as good and as quick footed as Salah. It is what we Gooners slate Mustafi for. On the plus side- Pépé was very good as were Guendouzi and Willock. Torreira and Lacazette also looked sharp when they came on. I had expected Unai to gave a set formation by now but he is still using horses-for-courses tactics (especially away from home) and today he used a rocking horse. I was amazed that while we were yielding chance after chance, he stood there watching. We had nothing to lose when 3-0 down but he did a Wenger and waited too long to make a formation and personnel change. Setting up as a 4-3-1-2 required us to execute the gameplan perfectly while hoping Liverpool were off form. The probability was low.

          How are WhoScored calculating average possession this season? Using Opta's "number of possessions" method, Arsenal have averaged 64.7% and using the chess clock "time with the ball" method, we've averaged 56%. We are listed, on the WS Premier League summary page, as having averaged 60%. The only way that works, in lieu of a formula which I'm unaware of being used, is if you take the average of the average of both methods (60.35%, rounded down to 60%). That doesnt work when looking at Liverpool's totals, however. #Possesions= 60.9%; TWTB= 58.5%; Avg of avg= 59.7%; WS avg= 56.7%.
